body:
Here are two samples of source code - a [Rust sample](https://rust.godbolt.org/z/7er15d) compiled with Rust 1.46.0 using the `thumbv4m-none-eabi` target, and a [C sample](https://godbolt.org/z/nPqGaP) compiled using clang 10.0.0. (The results are identical using Rust nightly and clang trunk.) They are as far as I can tell functionally identical.
```rust
#![no_std]

#[repr(C)]
pub struct Color {
    pub red: u8,
    pub green: u8,
    pub blue: u8,
}

pub extern "C" fn convert(color: Color) -> u16 {
    ((((color.red >> 3) & 0x1F) as u16) << 0)
    | ((((color.green >> 3) & 0x1F) as u16) << 5)
    | ((((color.blue >> 3) & 0x1F) as u16) << 10)
}
```
```c
#include <stdint.h>

struct Color {
    uint8_t red;
    uint8_t green;
    uint8_t blue;
};

uint16_t convert(struct Color color) {
    return (((color.red >> 3) & 0x1F) << 0)
        | (((color.green >> 3) & 0x1F) << 5)
        | (((color.blue >> 3) & 0x1F) << 10);
}
```
However, Rust is one instruction slower, and appears to be missing an optimisation - clang calculates `0x1F << 10` and delays adding together the intermediate values until the very end, whereas Rust starts with `0x1F << 5` and therefore has to perform an extra `mov`.
